      ],
      "kwargs": {
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "{\"success\":true,\"process_rule_id\":\"J09D\",\"process_rule\":\"1. Copy all rows from the given meter-reading decision table into a new temporary table `J09D_temp`, but only those rows where the tour identifier starts with `\\\"J09D\\\"`.\\n\\n2. In table `J09D_temp`, add a new column named `ENTSCHEIDUNG` (initially empty).\\n\\n3. In `J09D_temp`, classify meter-reading type by populating `ENTSCHEIDUNG` using these rules:\\n   - For each `HAUS`, count how many distinct `EQUNR` are associated with that `HAUS`.\\n   - If a `HAUS` has fewer than 3 `EQUNR`, set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \\\"KSA\\\"` for all rows of that `HAUS`; else set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \\\"EVU\\\"` for all rows of that `HAUS`.\\n   - Then, for all rows where `HOUSE_NUM1 = 0`, override and set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \\\"EVU\\\"`.\\n\\n4. Join `J09D_temp` with the `EABLG` table using the `INSTALLATION` column as the join key, producing a working joined table that retains all needed fields from both tables.\\n\\n5. Take this working table and join it with the `NET_MASTER` and `SALES_MASTER` tables using `EQUNR` as the join key, so that each record contains both net and sales customer master data where available.\\n\\n6. For each record in the joined dataset, compare the customer data from `SALES_MASTER` and `NET_MASTER` to determine whether sales customer data is present (non-empty) for that record.\\n\\n7. For each record in the joined dataset, choose which customer data to use:\\n   - If the sales customer data for this record is not empty:\\n     - Use the sales customer data table entries as the customer data for this record.\\n   - Else:\\n     - Use the net data customer table entries as the customer data for this record.\\n\\n8. From the resulting final dataset (after choosing sales vs net data per record), export the data to a CSV file named `J09D` and ensure the CSV has exactly these column names in the exported header (and corresponding data columns):\\n   - `\\\"Meter Reading (MR) Doc. No.\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"HAUS\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"ANLAGE\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"ME_MA_ID\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"EQUNR\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"HOUSE_NUM1\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"ENTSCHEIDUNG\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"TITLE\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"FORENAME\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"SURNAME\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"STREET\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"STREETNO\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"POST_CODE1\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"CITY1\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"CITY2\\\"`\\n   - `\\\"EMAIL\\\"`\\n\\n9. Send an email to EVU with the exported CSV file attached:\\n   - Use recipient email address: `meter.readings@evu.com`.\\n   - Attach the CSV file from `<path_to_exported_csv_file>` (the path where the `J09D` CSV was saved).\\n\\n10. After the email has been sent successfully, delete the temporary table `J09D_temp` to clean up.\"}",
            "id": "lc_e14af442-757b-4222-83ec-7eee5b5e1031"
          }
        ],
        "type": "tool",
        "name": "retrieve_process",
        "id": "a21bf01a-7b8d-48a1-9ff5-94fd86fd56ad",
        "tool_call_id": "call_FAgserPfCjd1iH1Wg1camtpQ",
        "artifact": {
          "structured_content": {
            "success": true,
            "process_rule_id": "J09D",
            "process_rule": "1. Copy all rows from the given meter-reading decision table into a new temporary table `J09D_temp`, but only those rows where the tour identifier starts with `\"J09D\"`.\n\n2. In table `J09D_temp`, add a new column named `ENTSCHEIDUNG` (initially empty).\n\n3. In `J09D_temp`, classify meter-reading type by populating `ENTSCHEIDUNG` using these rules:\n   - For each `HAUS`, count how many distinct `EQUNR` are associated with that `HAUS`.\n   - If a `HAUS` has fewer than 3 `EQUNR`, set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \"KSA\"` for all rows of that `HAUS`; else set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \"EVU\"` for all rows of that `HAUS`.\n   - Then, for all rows where `HOUSE_NUM1 = 0`, override and set `ENTSCHEIDUNG = \"EVU\"`.\n\n4. Join `J09D_temp` with the `EABLG` table using the `INSTALLATION` column as the join key, producing a working joined table that retains all needed fields from both tables.\n\n5. Take this working table and join it with the `NET_MASTER` and `SALES_MASTER` tables using `EQUNR` as the join key, so that each record contains both net and sales customer master data where available.\n\n6. For each record in the joined dataset, compare the customer data from `SALES_MASTER` and `NET_MASTER` to determine whether sales customer data is present (non-empty) for that record.\n\n7. For each record in the joined dataset, choose which customer data to use:\n   - If the sales customer data for this record is not empty:\n     - Use the sales customer data table entries as the customer data for this record.\n   - Else:\n     - Use the net data customer table entries as the customer data for this record.\n\n8. From the resulting final dataset (after choosing sales vs net data per record), export the data to a CSV file named `J09D` and ensure the CSV has exactly these column names in the exported header (and corresponding data columns):\n   - `\"Meter Reading (MR) Doc. No.\"`\n   - `\"HAUS\"`\n   - `\"ANLAGE\"`\n   - `\"ME_MA_ID\"`\n   - `\"EQUNR\"`\n   - `\"HOUSE_NUM1\"`\n   - `\"ENTSCHEIDUNG\"`\n   - `\"TITLE\"`\n   - `\"FORENAME\"`\n   - `\"SURNAME\"`\n   - `\"STREET\"`\n   - `\"STREETNO\"`\n   - `\"POST_CODE1\"`\n   - `\"CITY1\"`\n   - `\"CITY2\"`\n   - `\"EMAIL\"`\n\n9. Send an email to EVU with the exported CSV file attached:\n   - Use recipient email address: `meter.readings@evu.com`.\n   - Attach the CSV file from `<path_to_exported_csv_file>` (the path where the `J09D` CSV was saved).\n\n10. After the email has been sent successfully, delete the temporary table `J09D_temp` to clean up."
          }
        },
        "status": "success"
      }
    },
